No amount of magic can fix a blurry pic! But I had to share because what a reunion this lunch was! 

So many people coming together with Mayor Bass to build back Hollywood — and I hope Brushstroke Ventures can help even more marginalized young adults get off the streets and into better lives of their own design in tandem with the business community.

Hollywood counts— the most famous neighborhood in the entire world — the neighborhood I landed in when I came from Kenya. The neighborhood where I bartended for 8 years in the 90s. The neighborhood which drives tourism for the whole city. 🎥

Listening to Mayor Bass was inspiring. I believe. ⭐️ We can invite new thinking to the table and repair the world. 

Seen here with Television City @tvc.studios — their community development plan for Beverly Fairfax is one we should all support- walkable streets, trees!

Trying to balance my IG burn out with the desire to share stories. I didn’t shoot this and was about to walk away from lunch and goodbyes when the phone came out … 

📷 Why is this pic worth sharing? 

Because every day more kids fall into foster care, homelessness or incarceration. 

If we don’t get our heads out of our assess and fix our core foundational systems - poverty, education, mental health to name three - then we will always scramble to pick up these pieces downstream which benefits NO ONE

This approach:
1. Has a massive human capital cost for us all - we should not ever accept that we have hurt people among us and not help 

2. Deprives us ALL of the incredible thinking and new ways of seeing the world that we never get because some populations of people are not giving the same access 

3. Is the most pathetic way to spend tax dollars when we could just invest in fixing the damn drip at the faucet and put our tax dollars to make our communities better - you know - thing like more art, music, trees and parks 

Our status-quo isn’t working and we don’t have to sit back and accept that it is - go forth and do something good 

Plant a tree, help a human, adopt a dog damn it

Whatever you think you know about Israel, you are probably wrong (I lived on a kibbutz that bordered Gaza for many months). 

Whatever you think of Israel’s current leadership, you could be correct. We elected Trump. Hate and power-lust lives alongside us too. 

Being Jewish is a religious choice (I’m atheist) but not an ethnic one. Being Jewish is genetic and we all come from one place - ancient Middle East. Called Israelites before Jews (500 BCE) Jews originated in the Levant around 1000 BCE - modern Israel.

Abolish “Israel” is code for abolish Jews. 

Comparisons to Nazism and Hitler set the stage for complicity in the most extreme extermination campaign in the world - the Holocaust - only 75 years ago. 

The crazy thing is also according to the poster on Next Door each time he paints over this hate speech, the author returns the next day to paint it again. That’s how much Jews are hated. 

We can spend a lot of time hating each other, or we can realize that we are all exactly the same only separated perhaps by slightly different belief systems or maybe the color of our skin - but we all feel the same pain. We all share the desire to love and be loved.

Let’s remind ourselves of that frequently.

Found this dusting off some old files … the first fundraiser 2005

This was organized about six months after I incorporated the idea to build an art school for homeless, marginalized over 18 young adults with the IRS.

We honored video game pioneer Tommy Tallarico @tommytallarico, took over a sound state at Raleigh Studios, and welcomed a full orchestra + 3 opera singers ….

I very boldly allied with the video game industry at a time when they were under attack from the federal government for Grand Theft Auto and corrupting youth 

that relationship allowed us to raise over 100,000 and open the doors to a school within weeks!

Now we’re back - bigger … and keep in mind — 2005. Listen to the speakers we all knew we had built an incredibly broken system. We just all chose to ignore it except for those of us who didn’t.
